        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(ollama): release stream reader lock to prevent resource leak",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\n\n`extensions/ollama/src/stream.ts` acquires a `ReadableStreamDefaultReader` via `response.body.getReader()` inside a try block, but the finally block that calls `release()` did not call `reader.releaseLock()`. Per the Streams specification, `releaseLock()` is required to release the lock on the underlying stream — without it, the stream remains locked after the function returns.\n\nAdditionally, the original `const reader` declaration inside the try block caused a TypeScript error: the finally block cannot reference a const that is not guaranteed to be assigned in all code paths (error paths throw before reader assignment).\n\n## Changes\n\n- `extensions/ollama/src/stream.ts`: hoist `reader` declaration before try block → `let reader: ReadableStreamDefaultReader<Uint8Array> | undefined`\n- Assign `reader` inside try: `reader = response.body.getReader()`\n- In finally: `reader?.releaseLock()` (optional chaining for safety when try throws before assignment)\n\nLabel: bugfix | merge-risk: 🟢 minimal | AI-assisted\n\n## Evidence\n\n### Code path analysis\n\nBefore the fix:\n```\ntry {\n  reader = body.getReader()   // may throw before this line\n  while(true) { read() }      // stream processing\n} finally {\n  // reader might be unassigned → TS error\n  await release()\n}\n```\n\nAfter the fix:\n```\nlet reader: ... | undefined\ntry {\n  reader = body.getReader()   // safe: declared outside\n  while(true) { read() }\n} finally {\n  reader?.releaseLock()       // safe: optional chaining\n  await release()\n}\n```\n\nThe `?.` operator ensures that if the try block throws before `reader` is assigned (e.g., non-OK response, empty body), the finally block degrades gracefully to a no-op for `releaseLock()` while still executing `await release()`.\n\n### Reference\n\nPer the Streams specification: \"A ReadableStream reader lock is released by calling `reader.releaseLock()`. This must be called even after `reader.cancel()` — cancel rejects pending reads but does not release the lock.\"",
